@BenjaminDowns
Yes, you can get away with using objects if you're building the object using Object Literals, but what happens if you try to programmatically add new keys to your object?
```javascript
let hundreds = {slot: 5, name: "hundreds"}, twenties = {slot: 4, name: "twenties"}, tens = {slot: 3, name: "tens"}, fives = {slot: 2, name: "fives"}, ones = {slot: 1, name: "ones"};
drawer[hundreds] = 200;
drawer[twenties] = 40;
drawer[tens] = 20;
drawer[fives] = 10;
drawer[ones] = 5;
```
You would expect the outcome to be:
```javascript
drawer = {
  {slot: 5, name: "hundreds"}: 200,
  {slot: 4, name: "twenties"}: 40,
  {slot: 3, name: "tens"}: 20,
  {slot: 2, name: "fives"}: 10,
  {slot: 1, name: "ones"}: 5
}
```
But what you end up getting is:
```javascript
drawer = {
  "[object Object]": 5
}
```
All values were overwritten in the `drawer` object, because javascript converted Object Keys (e.g. `{slot: 5, name: "hundreds"}`) to Strings (e.g. `"[object Object]"`)
